HAND_GESTURE_ENABLED_SECURITY_SYSTEM_WITH_RC4_ENCRYPTION



ABSTRACT:

            This project presents a smart, contactless access control solution—Hand Gesture Enabled Security System—integrated with RC4 encryption and email notification via Resend API. Aimed at enhancing hygiene and security, the system enables users to unlock doors through predefined hand gestures detected by the PAJ7620U2 sensor. The Arduino Uno microcontroller processes these gestures and interacts with a 16×2 LCD for real-time feedback. To ensure robust protection of access credentials, RC4 encryption secures stored passwords and verifies gesture-authenticated users. Additionally, the system incorporates Resend API to send instant email alerts upon unauthorized access attempts, providing real-time monitoring capabilities. The solution is low-cost, scalable, and highly relevant in smart homes, offices, and healthcare environments. It demonstrates strong gesture recognition accuracy (≈95%) and swift response (1–2 seconds), offering a hygienic alternative to conventional locks. The project not only enhances user experience through touchless interaction but also contributes to modernizing access control systems with encryption and IoT-based alerts.

NOVELTY:

• PAJ7620 gesture recognition sensor which captures 9 predefined gestures in real-time.
• Customizable gestures for specific functions like "open", "lock", "denied", etc.
• A hands-free, hygienic interface that can function in various lighting conditions and doesn't require physical contact or authentication tokens.
• RC4 encryption for secure password storage and verification.
• Resend API integration for reliable, real-time security email notifications.

OBJECTIVE:

	The project aims to develop a secure and efficient door access system that uses gesture control by integrating PAJ7620 gesture sensor with Arduino Uno. It uses a 16×2 LCD to provide real-time feedback on gesture recognition and access status. RC4 encryption enhances security by protecting access codes. The Resend API enables reliable email notifications that alert owners of unauthorized access attempts. The system will be tested for accuracy and reliability to ensure proper access control. This solution offers a cost-effective, hygienic, and scalable alternative for contactless door locking in smart homes, offices, and healthcare environments.

ARCHITECTURE: 
     The "Hand Gesture-Enabled Door Access Control System" integrates an Arduino Uno, PAJ7620U2 gesture sensor, RC4 encryption algorithm, and a 16×2 LCD display to create a secure and hygienic access mechanism. This contactless system replaces traditional access methods with smart gesture recognition, providing a touch-free, user-friendly solution ideal for environments requiring both convenience and enhanced hygiene.
 
	
•	The Arduino Uno functions as the central processing unit of the system. It receives gesture input from the PAJ7620U2 sensor, interprets it using a gesture recognition algorithm, and makes access control decisions based on predefined valid gesture patterns.
•	The gesture sensor detects up to 9 unique hand gestures in real time (e.g., up, down, left, right, forward, backward, clockwise, counter-clockwise, and wave), allowing the user to unlock or lock the system via specific movements.
•	Once a valid gesture sequence is identified, the RC4 encryption algorithm is applied to verify the encrypted access code stored in the Arduino. This ensures that even if the system is compromised, unauthorized access attempts cannot decrypt the stored credentials.
•	The 16×2 LCD display provides immediate feedback to the user, displaying messages such as "Access Granted", "Access Denied", or "Invalid Gesture", ensuring clarity and ease of use.
•	In case of an unauthorized or invalid gesture input, the system automatically triggers an email notification using the Resend API, alerting the system administrator or user in real time. This ensures quick responses to potential security breaches.
This modular, low-cost prototype demonstrates a secure, efficient, and hygienic solution for door access control that can be easily scaled or integrated with IoT infrastructure for enhanced functionality in smart homes, healthcare institutions, office spaces, and other secured environments.
PAJ7620 Gesture Recognition Sensor
 
PAJ7620U2 integrates gesture recognition function with general I2C interface into a single chip. It can recognize 9 gestures and the gesture information can simply access via the I2C bus.
Gesture recognition function:
•	Move up
•	Move down
•	Move left
•	Move right
•	Move forward
•	Move backward
•	Circle-clockwise
•	Circle-counter clockwise
•	Wave
Mechanism:
The PAJ7620 sensor emits infrared light and detects the reflection of this light off objects, such as a hand. It has an array of photodiodes that measure the intensity of the reflected light. 
By analysing the pattern of these intensities, the sensor can recognize various gestures, such as swipes, circles, and waves. Once a gesture is recognized, the sensor generates an output signal, which can be used by a microcontroller to perform specific tasks based on the gesture.
