METHODOLOGY:

                The methodology began with designing the system, selecting components like the Arduino Uno and PAJ7620 sensor for gesture recognition. The Arduino was programmed to process gestures and control an LCD for feedback. After hardware setup, the system was tested to ensure accurate gesture detection and proper feedback. Calibration was done to minimize errors, and adjustments were made for better performance. RC4 encryption was implemented for password security. The Resend API integration facilitated real-time email notifications. Finally, real-world testing validated the system's functionality, ensuring intuitive and secure operation.

MOTIVATION
The rise in demand for contactless technologies in the wake of safety concerns (e.g. COVID-19) and the need for inclusive design for differently-abled individuals inspired this project. Traditional access methods often involve physical contact and may pose hygiene issues or be inaccessible to users with mobility challenges. Furthermore, the advancement in human-computer interaction, particularly gesture recognition, motivated the development of this innovative system that makes door access smarter, safer, more convenient, and with encrypted security.

MODULES
The system includes key modules: the Gesture Sensor Module uses the PAJ7620U2 sensor to detect gestures like up, down, left, right, clockwise, counter-clockwise, forward, backward, and wave. The Microcontroller Unit powered by an Arduino Uno processes gestures and controls access via C/C++ programming in the Arduino IDE. The Display Module features a 16×2 LCD that shows status updates. The Security Module implements RC4 encryption for password protection. The Notification Module uses Resend API to deliver instant email alerts on unauthorized access attempts.

